    "Let me analyze this reaction to identify the roles of reagents, solvent, and catalyst.\n\nThe reaction SMILES is:\nC=CC(=C)CCCCC(N)=O.CC(C)=O.COC(=O)C=O>>C=CC(=C)CCCCC(=O)NC(O)C(=O)OC\n\nLet me parse the reactants:\n1. C=CC(=C)CCCCC(N)=O - This is citronellamide or a similar amide (2,6-dimethyl-6-heptenamide) - an amide with an NH2 group\n2. CC(C)=O - This is acetone\n3. COC(=O)C=O - This is methyl glyoxylate (methyl oxoacetate)\n\nThe product is:\nC=CC(=C)CCCCC(=O)NC(O)C(=O)OC - This is an N-acyl amino acid derivative where the amide nitrogen has been acylated with a glyoxylate unit, forming an amide bond and adding an OH group.\n\nLooking at the mapped reaction:\n- [CH2:1]=[CH:2][C:3](=[CH2:4])[CH2:5][CH2:6][CH2:7][CH2:8][C:9]([NH2:11])=[O:10] - the amide\n- CC(C)=O - acetone (unmapped)\n- [CH3:17][O:16][C:14](=[O:15])[CH:12]=[O:13] - methyl glyoxylate\n\nProduct:\n- [CH2:1]=[CH:2][C:3](=[CH2:4])[CH2:5][CH2:6][CH2:7][CH2:8][C:9](=[O:10])[NH:11][CH:12]([OH:13])[C:14](=[O:15])[O:16][CH3:17]\n\nSo the amide NH2 reacts with the aldehyde of methyl glyoxylate to form an N-acyl hemiaminal (the NH attacks the aldehyde, and the OH comes from the aldehyde oxygen). The amide C=O becomes part of the new amide linkage.\n\nWait, let me reconsider. The amide C(=O)NH2 becomes C(=O)NH- in the product. The NH2 loses one H and forms a bond to the CH of glyoxylate. The glyoxylate CHO becomes CH(OH) in the product. So this is a condensation between the amide nitrogen and the aldehyde of methyl glyoxylate, forming a hemiaminal.\n\nNow what about acetone? Acetone is unmapped in the reaction, meaning it doesn't appear in the product. This strongly suggests acetone is the solvent.\n\nSo the roles are:\n- C=CC(=C)CCCCC(N)=O (the amide) - Reactant (substrate)\n- COC(=O)C=O (methyl glyoxylate) - Reactant (reagent)\n- CC(C)=O (acetone) - Solvent\n\nThere's no catalyst mentioned in this reaction.\n\nLet me format this as a condition_role_mapping:\n\nReactants:\n1. C=CC(=C)CCCCC(N)=O - substrate\n2. COC(=O)C=O - reagent\n3. CC(C)=O - solvent\n\nNo catalyst is identified."
